<chapter xml:id="ch_forces" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Force Models</title>
<introduction>
    <p>We will now begin a new topic, perhaps the most foundational in all of physics: Forces.</p>
		
	<p><alert>Learning Outcomes</alert></p>
		
		<p>After successful completion of this chapter, you will be able to:
		<ol>
		  <li>Differentiate between contact forces and non-contact forces</li>
		  <li>State and apply Newton's laws</li>
		  <li>Draw a free-body diagram of an object or multiple objects in a system</li>
		  <li>Define the normal force acting on an object in various situations</li>
		  <li>Define tension in a system</li>
		  <li>Construct net force equations in multiple dimensions for an object based on its acceleration and its free-body diagram</li>
		  <li>Solve net force equations symbolically in terms of given variables</li>
		  <li>Include friction force acting between two objects at rest or in motion</li>
		  <li>Identify Newton's third law force pairs</li>
		  <li>Analyze systems of massive objects and pulleys of negligible mass using a force approach</li>
		</ol>
		</p>

</introduction>

